I remember a local story, it was either a wedding or at the baptism of a baby (details are a bit muddy), but the best man/godfather and maid of honor/godmother turned out to both not be baptized because they were born during the communist era and their parents were not religious.

They found out just before the ceremony was about to start and the Bulgarian Orthodox priest just proceeded to dunk them both in some water to baptize them and got it done in 10 minutes, then proceeded with the ceremony. No need to waste time.

The way the Semitic words "Baal" and "El" for "Lord" and "God" themselves turned into idolatrized deities distinct from Yahweh reminds me of H. P. Lovecraft's short story "Ibid" where the abbreviation "ibid." is taken to be a scholar named Ibidus who wrote in the 5th-6th century.

I guess it's what Dr. Ray Peat talks about, some cultures get too obsessed with words and names and start to think they are a separate thing from the reality they point to. So you just call God "God" too many times and eventually start to think "God" is a separate thing from God.
